  <sect2 id="detailsjoining">
   <title>Details on Joining Particular Parts of GNOME</title>
   <para>
    This section describes how a new contributor can get started
    in his or her particular area of interest.
   </para>
   <sect3 id="joininggap">
    <title>Joining the GNOME Accessibility Project (GAP)</title>
    <para>
     The <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gap">GNOME Accessibility
     Project</ulink> makes GNOME accessible to people with
     disabilities.  Anybody who is interested in contributing to the
     GNOME Accessibility Project should visit <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gap/contrib.html">
     Contributing to the Gnome Accessibility Project</ulink>.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joininggdp">
    <title>Joining the GNOME Documentation Project (GDP)</title>
    <para>
     The <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gdp">GNOME Documentation
     Project</ulink> oversees the writing, editing, and indexing
     of all GNOME documentation (user and developer) as well as the
     <ulink type="http" url="http://developer.gnome.org">GNOME
     Developer Web Pages</ulink>.  New members are encouraged
     to join the <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://mail.gnome.org/mailman/listinfo/gnome-doc-list/">
     gnome-doc-list mailing list</ulink> and look over 
     <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gdp/handbook.html">
     <citetitle>The GNOME Handbook of Writing Software 
     Documentation</citetitle></ulink>
     (also known as the <citetitle>GDP Handbook</citetitle>).
     Further information on joining the GDP can be found 
     <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gdp/join.html">
     here</ulink>. New contributors may want to look through
     the <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gdp/tasks.html">
     GDP Tasks</ulink> and some of the recent <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gdp/status/">GDP Status
     Reports</ulink>.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joininggtp">
    <title>Joining the GNOME Translation Project (GTP)</title>
    <para>
     The <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gtp">GNOME Translation 
     Project</ulink> translates application strings as well as 
     application manuals and other GNOME documents.  To join the
     GTP, you should first determine if a translation team 
     exists for the language you would like to translate into.  You
     can do this by checking the <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gtp/teams.html">translation
     teams list</ulink>. If a contact is listed, you should contact
     this person and express your interest in helping.  If no contact
     person is listed, you should consider starting a translation 
     team as described <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gtp/teams.html#starting">here
     </ulink>.  All translators should consider joining the 
     <ulink url="http://mail.gnome.org/mailman/listinfo/gnome-i18n/"
     type="http">gnome-i18n-list</ulink> mailing list.  New translators
     should find <ulink type="http"
     url="http://developer.gnome.org/projects/gtp/translate-gnome/index.html">
     Translation of the GNOME desktop environment</ulink> helpful.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joininggraphics">
    <title>Getting Started Contributing Graphics to GNOME</title>
    <para>
     GNOME does not yet have a GNOME Graphics Project.  We may consider
     forming one in the future.  If you are interested in producing 
     icons or graphics for the GNOME desktop, 
     contact <ulink url="mailto:tigert@gimp.org">Tuomas Kuosmanen</ulink>
     and <ulink url="mailto:mawa@iname.com">Matthias Warkus</ulink>.
     If you are interested in producing graphics for the web pages
     or GNOME applications, contact the <link linkend="joiningweb">
     coordinators for the web pages</link>
     or applications directly.  If you are interested in starting a
     GNOME Graphics Project, contact the <ulink 
     url="mailto:d-mueth@uchicago.edu">author of this 
     document</ulink>.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningui">
    <title>Getting Started with User Interface Design</title>
    <para>
     User interface and human interface design is done by the
     <ulink url="http://developer.gnome.org/gnome-ui/">GNOME
     User Interface Improvement Project</ulink>. It has a 
     mailing list called <ulink type="http"
     url="http://mail.gnome.org/mailman/listinfo/gnome-gui-list">gnome-gui-list
	 </ulink>.  If you are interested in joining the GNOME User
     Interface Improvement Project, join the gnome-gui-list mailing
     list or contact its coordinator, <ulink 
     url="mailto:arlo@eazel.com">Arlo Rose</ulink>.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningsound">
    <title>Getting Started Contributing Sounds to GNOME</title>
    <para>
     GNOME is in the process of forming a GNOME Sound Project.  
     The first steps are to identify what work needs to be done,
     determine how the sounds will be licensed and packaged,
     and determine what tools are suitable. To join in the 
     discussion, subscribe to the <ulink type="http"
     url="http://mail.gnome.org/mailman/listinfo/gnome-sound-list">
     gnome-sound-list</ulink> mailing list.  Feel free to start
     creating your own sound theme for GNOME desktop events.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningpackaging">
    <title>Getting Started Packaging GNOME</title>
    <para>
     If you would like to help package GNOME applications, contact
     the authors of the applications you would like to package.
     Generally application authors do not want to spend a lot of 
     time packaging their software and would be happy to have your
     help. If you would like to create a new GNOME package containing
     multiple related applications, email <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gnome-devel-list/">
     gnome-devel-list</ulink> with a description of your plans.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningweb">
    <title>Getting Started On GNOME Web Development</title>
    <para>
     Send an email to 
     <ulink url="mailto:joakim@helixcode.com">Joakim Ziegler</ulink>
     for <ulink url="http://www.gnome.org"
     type="http">www.gnome.org</ulink> or 
     <ulink url="mailto:dcm@redhat.com,d-mueth@uchicago.edu">Dave 
     Mason and Dan Mueth</ulink> for
     <ulink url="http://developer.gnome.org"
     type="http">developer.gnome.org</ulink> 
     indicating what you are interested in working on. It 
     will help the maintainers find a good project
     for you to start with if you describe any relevant skills or 
     experience you have.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningtesting">
    <title>Getting Started Testing GNOME</title>
    <para>
     GNOME does not currently have an official testing project.
     Testing is typically done by individuals who report
     any bugs they find to Bugzilla.  Most GNOME bugs should be 
     reported to <ulink type="http" url="http://bugs.gnome.org/">
     bugs.gnome.org</ulink>, although for 
     <application>Nautilus</application> they go to <ulink
     type="http" url="http://bugzilla.eazel.com/">bugzilla.eazel.com
     </ulink> and for <application>Helix GNOME</application>,
     <application>Evolution</application>, and several other GNOME
     components they go to <ulink url="http://bugzilla.helixcode.com/"
     type="http">bugzilla.helixcode.com</ulink>. The 
     <application>Bug Buddy</application> application makes submitting
     bugs easy.  Anybody who has experience with setting up testing 
     guidelines, test cases, etc. should consider starting a GNOME
     Testing Project.
     (Note that Nautilus does have a testing project which can be
     found <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://nautilus.eazel.com/testing/">here</ulink>.)
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningdeveloping">
    <title>Getting Started Developing GNOME Applications</title>
    <para>
     First, you must decide what to work on.  If you are joining
     an existing project, contact the maintainers for that project.
     If you are starting a new application, make sure to check the 
     <ulink url="http://www.gnome.org/applist/list.php3"
     type="http">GNOME Software Map</ulink> to see if an application
     similar to the one you are planning does not exist.  If it does,
     consider joining the existing project. If you are not sure what
     you want to work on, then look in the <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://www.gnome.org/todo/index.php3">GNOME Todo
     Database</ulink> or consider joining an existing project.
     If you need help getting started developing, see <xref
     linkend="learningtodevelop">.  Make sure to register any new
     applications in the GNOME Todo Database.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joininggnomeplatform">
    <title>Getting Started Developing The GNOME Platform</title>
    <para>
     Email <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gnome-devel-list/">
     gnome-devel-list</ulink> with a description of the 
     improvements or additions you would like to make.
    </para>
   </sect3>
   <sect3 id="joiningtooldevelopment">
    <title>Getting Started Developing Developer Tools</title>
    <para>
     Developer tools are generally associated with a particular
     task and group of people (application developers, document
     writers, translators, graphic artists, sound editors, etc.)
     To develop tools for a particular group of people, you should
     contact the project coordinators (see <xref 
     linkend="contactperson">) and project members and determine 
     what the needs of the particular group are.  These tools 
     vary from relatively simple scripts and web applications 
     to very complex development tools.  Some suggestions for 
     tools which GNOME developers need are listed in the 
     <ulink type="http" 
     url="http://www.gnome.org/todo/index.php3">GNOME Todo
     Database</ulink>. 
    </para>
   </sect3>

  </sect2>

 </sect1>

 <!-- ============= Learning to Develop ========================== -->
 <sect1 id="learningtodevelop">
  <title>Learning to Develop</title>

  <para>
   GNOME is a great development platform largely because the 
   GNOME widgets and libraries handle many of the more tedious 
   tasks a developer must tackle, allowing the
   developer to focus on the primary parts of their application.
   Since the core GNOME development team has put a lot of work into
   developing these core GNOME technologies, they are generally of
   much higher quality than applications could typically have.
   Many of these technologies which are built into GNOME are new
   to developers who are accustomed to more traditional
   development environments.  If you are a developer who is new to GNOME,
   you will benefit substantially by exploring these powerful tools
   and using them to improve the power and stability of your application
   while reducing the necessary development time and effort.
  </para>

  <para>
   This section should help developers who are new to GNOME find
   information on the various GNOME technologies and other tools
   used by the GNOME project.
  </para>

