  <sect2 id="developerwp">
   <title>The GNOME Developer Web Pages</title>
   <para>
    Every developer who is considering GNOME as a development
    platform should look over <ulink type="http"
    url="http://developer.gnome.org">The GNOME Developer
    Web Pages</ulink>.  They provides much valuable information on
    the <ulink type="http" url="http://developer.gnome.org/arch/">GNOME 
    architecture</ulink> along with tutorials, white papers, and
    helpful links to other resources.  It also has information about
    the various <ulink url="http://developer.gnome.org/tools/" 
    type="http">tools</ulink> used by GNOME developers.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="ggad">
   <title>Gtk+/GNOME Application Development</title>
   <para>
    Havoc Pennington, one of the core GNOME developers, 
    wrote a very good book on GNOME application
    development called <citetitle>Gtk+/GNOME Application
    Development</citetitle>. It was published under an open license, meaning
    that you can either <ulink type="http"
    url="http://developer.gnome.org/doc/GGAD/">read it online </ulink>
    or purchase it in a bookstore or online by following the
    link <ulink type="http"
    url="http://www106.pair.com/rhp/gnome-app-devel.html">here</ulink>.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="gnome-hello">
   <title>gnome-hello: An example GNOME Application</title>
   <para>
    Havoc Pennington wrote an example GNOME application called
    <application>gnome-hello</application> which shows a new
    developer how to handle many aspects of writing a GNOME 
    application.  You can find it in CVS in the 
    <filename>gnome-hello</filename> module.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="gnometutorials">
   <title>GNOME Tutorials</title>
   <para>
    There are many GNOME tutorials which can help a new developer
    get started.  Many can be found in the <ulink type="http"
    url="http://developer.gnome.org/doc/">GNOME Developer 
    Documentation</ulink> portion of the GNOME Developer Web Pages.
    George Lebl also wrote an excellent series of tutorials for
    IBM DeveloperWorks which can be found by selecting 
    <quote>Lebl</quote> on their <ulink type="http" 
    url="http://www2.software.ibm.com/developer/papers.nsf/linux-papers-byauthor">
    author list page</ulink>. 
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="glade">
   <title>Glade: The GNOME Application Builder</title>
   <para>
    <ulink type="http" url="http://glade.pn.org/">Glade</ulink>
    is a tool for quickly prototyping GNOME applications and experimenting 
    with GNOME widgets.  It allows you to build your application's layout 
    by graphically pasting and configuring your widgets.
    Glade also generates much of the more tedious code needed such as
    the autoconf/automake scripts, header files, translation potfiles,
    and most of the application code except the actual content
    of the callback functions.
    More information can be found <ulink type="http"
    url="http://developer.gnome.org/arch/devel/glade.html">here</ulink>
    and by reading the documents that ship with Glade and are accessible
    by selecting the <guimenu>Help</guimenu> menu items.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="cvs">
   <title>Getting Application Source From CVS</title>
   <para>
    Most GNOME applications are stored in GNOME CVS, which is open to
    the public for download.  One of the first tasks a new GNOME
    developer must do is figure out how to download code from CVS.
    For a brief introduction to CVS, read this <ulink type="http"
    url="http://developer.gnome.org/tools/cvs.html">short 
    CVS tutorial</ulink>.
   </para>
  </sect2>

 </sect1>

 <!-- =========== Adding Applications to GNOME =========== -->
 <sect1 id="addingapps">
  <title>Adding Applications to GNOME</title>


  <para>
   Often application developers would like to make their GNOME-based 
   application or applet part of GNOME. This may be done by either
   including the application in one of the core GNOME packages, 
   adding the application or applet to the <quote>extra</quote>
   GNOME applications list, or adding the 
   application to the GNOME Software Map.
  </para>

  <sect2 id="addingappscore">
   <title>Adding Applications to Core GNOME Packages</title>
   <para>
    If you would like to add an application to one of the 
    standard GNOME packages such as gnome-applets, gnome-utils,
    gnome-media, or gnome-games, you should contact the maintainer
    of the package.  The maintainer of the package can be found
    by reading the <filename>MAINTAINERS</filename> file in the 
    CVS module for the package or by consulting the <xref 
    linkend="contactperson">.  Note that any package in GNOME CVS
    which has a <filename>MAINTAINERS</filename> file should
    have a mailing list associated with it which is at 
    &lt;packagename&gt;-maint@gnome.org and forwards to all of the 
    email addresses in the <filename>MAINTAINERS</filename> file.
    This is generally a great way to contact all of the maintainers
    of a module. Also note that only stable applications
    should be added to these packages.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="addingtoapprovedlist">
   <title>Adding Applications to the <quote>extra</quote> GNOME Application 
    List</title>
   <para>
    In addition to the core GNOME distribution, each GNOME release
    starting with GNOME 1.4 will be accompanied by an <quote>extra</quote>
    set of applications.  These applications will be tested and certified
    to work with the release.  They must pass a certain set of requirements
    to qualify.  To suggest that your application be added to this list,
    email <ulink type="http" 
    url="http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gnome-devel-list/">
    gnome-devel-list</ulink> and ask for the coordinator for
    the <quote>extra</quote> GNOME package list.
   </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2 id="addingtosoftwaremap">
   <title>Adding Applications to the GNOME Software Map</title>
   <para>
    The <ulink url="http://www.gnome.org/applist/list.php3"
    type="http">GNOME Software Map</ulink> is a web-based resource 
    which keeps track of GNOME applications.  It sorts the 
    applications by subject and lists information about each 
    application such as its description, web page, version, and where
    to download the application from. Each time a new version of 
    the application is released, an announcement of the release 
    is posted on the front page of <ulink type="http"
    url="http://www.gnome.org">www.gnome.org</ulink>.  All GNOME
    application authors are encouraged to register their application(s)
    in the GNOME Software Map and update the entry every time a new
    release is made.
   </para>
  </sect2>

 </sect1>

